{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866779/1930040501/0219.xml":{"full_text":"^enitmla Enterprise\nFounded by\nJOHN W. EDMONDS\nJune 30. 1881 i\nALFRED B. G. EDMONDS\nJOHN W. EDMONDS. Jr.\nOwners and Publishers\nAOOOMAC COURT-HOUSE, VA.\nEntered at the Postoffice at Accomac;\ndL H, Va\u201e as Second-class Matter, i\nSATURDAY, APRIL 5, 1000\nI\nI\nTHE BUSINESS OUTLOOK\nEver since the stock market crash\nlast fall many conflicting opinions'\nJuwe been expressed concerning thei\n4msiMss outlook for 1930. There is j\nno denying the fact that there has;\ntmi a slowing down in certain lines,\nbat the views of leading industrial-;\njgts and business men appear quite j\nOptimistic with the.advent of Spring.,\n\u2022There is no doubt that the con- j\ncertetf effort of these leaders to'\nmaintain high levels of production\nand distribution is having a whole\nsale effect. Besides, large expen\nditures for permanent improvements\nty Federal State awl local authori-,\n-tfess are getting under way, while\nbillions are involved in expansion\nprograms of railroads, utilities and(,\nother basic industries.\n1 An especially favorable trend is\n-IX. in the direction of home build-\ning and home improvement, concern-j\ning which a significant statement\nwas made last week after a nation\nwide survey by Altorfer Bros., who\nsaid: \"Home construction is up 425 j\nper cent since 1920, and wired homes\nhave doubled in the intervening 10\nyears. Various leading electrical\nhome equipment distributors through- j\nout the United States reveal com- i\nprehensive plans to build new busi-,;\nness during the year. There need,\nbe no apprehension; indeed, there\ncan be \"only optimism regarding\n1330.\u201d i,\nEncouraging reports have been,\nforthcoming from many other sources^\nM it appears that the temporary de-|\npreesion may soon be ended.\nA BIRTHDAY PARTY\nBirthday honors such as few men,\nhave ever received will be accorded;\nDr- William Henry Welch, of Johns;\nHopkins University on his 80th birth-,\nday anniversary, April 8. The cele-,\nbraition will be international inj\nscope, with simultaneous gatherings;\nof Dr. Welch\u2019s friends, colleagues:\nand former-students in Washington, j\nLondon, Paris, Berlin, Leipzig, Tokio.j\nPeiping, New York and other cities.,\nPresident Hoover will speak at the\nWashington celebration and pay tri-j\nbut* this noted physician and\neducator, known as the \u201cdean of.\nAmerican medicine.\u201d 1\nIn spite of his SO years, Dr.1\nWelch is still active as professor of\nthe history of medicine nt Johns\nHopkins, president of the Rockefel\nler medical research board and a\ntrustee of Carnegie Institution. He\nholds a\u2018number of foreign decora\ntions and about all the degrees and\nhonors the world has to bestow for\nprofessional attainment.\nThe committee in charge of the\nbirthday celebration said: \u201cAmerica\nowes more to Dr. Welch than can\never be told in any tributes. Through\nthe reforms which he has instituted\nin medical study, through his re\nsearches, the many hundreds of doc-j\ntors trained by him and the vital\npublic health measures which he has\ninspired, it is literally true that\nmillions have benefited from his con\ntribution.\"\nIt is eminently fitting that this;\ngrand old man of American medi- j\ncine should have an international]\nbirthday party upon attaining the!\nage of four score. Let us hope\nthat his years of usefulness may be!\nextended indefinitely.\nTHE NEW PLANET\nFor years astronomers have j\nsearched the heavens for a ninth j\nplanet, which mathematical calcula-1\ntions led them to believe existed be- j\nyond Neptune. Tt remained for a!\nyoung American observatory assist-!\nant, Clyde Tombaugh. 23 years old,!\nto find it.' It was not discovered di-j\nrectiy through a telescope, but as a!\nfaint spot of light on a photographic\nplate and later verified as the long\n-sought body.\nIt may be unknown to many that!\n\u25a0\u25a0this is the third planet of our solar j\n\u25a0system to be discovered by mat;\nduring the last 150 years. While!\nthe nearer planets were known to;\nthe ancients, Uranus was not dis\neovered until 1781, nor Neptune un\ntil 1846. 'Hie newly found planet\nhas not yet been named, nor has its\nsize been determined.\nIts distance from the sun i\nthought to be between three and\nfour billion miles, while the earth\nis a little less than 93 million miles\nfrom our central luminary. So,\nwhile it is interesting to know that\nwe have an additional member of\nour solar system, its presence will\nhave little effect upon practical af\nfairs.\nA few days after the discovery of\nthe ninth planet was announced, an\nItalian amateur astronomer claimed\nthat he had found four tie\"' rdanets,\nmaking 13 in all, but so far his\nclaim has not been verified by any\nrecognized authorities.\nDEATHS\ni\nMr. Wm. F. Juslis\nMr. William F. Justis, of Clam,\na highly respected citizen, died at\nthe home of his daughter, Mrs. Wr.\nF. Kilmon, Xew Church. Va., Tues\nday, April 1st, aged T(> years.\nFuneral services were held at St.\nThomas Methodist Church. Clam.\nVa., Thursday, A y.r'l ;:rd. conducted\nby Iris pa-tor. llev. V. Johnston\nand interment was in f.lu.rty Ceme\ntery, Parksley.\nThe active pallbearers were Mes-j\nsrs. Edward Justis, Charles Justis,\nWm. Justis, George 11. Justis. Sam\nJustis, Wilbur Taylor. Tiie honor\nary pallbeareirs were Messrs. John,\nTaylor, Edgar Taylor, Lemuel'\nKarnes, Lester Parks, C.e^-ge P.j\nBarnes and Eugene Parks.\nHe is survived by four daughters, i\nMrs, James F. Fast, of Onley, Mrs.\nI. C. Justus, of Clam, Mrs. W. F.!\nKilmon, of Xew Church and Mrs.\nLloyd Kilnipn, of Parksley. i\nMisr. Mary E. Grant\nMiss Man- E. Grant, sister of the\nate John D. Grant, died at her home I\nit Leemont, Ya., Monday, March 31, j\nif paralysis, aged eighty-two years.\nFuneral services were held at the j\ntome of her nieces, Misses Tibbie\nind Susie Grant. Accomac, Va.,\nWednesday, April 2nd, conducted by|\nSev. W. A. Donoway, pastor of Lee- j\nnont M. 1\u2019. Church, of which she i\nvas a member, assisted by Rev. R.j\n3. Bryant and interment was in i\nSdge Hill Cemetery-.\nThe pallbearers were Messrs. John j\nL'hurn, Asher Justis, YV. T. Melson,!\nr. C. Ayres, Rogers Ayres and Dr. i\nra Hurst.\nMiss Grant is survived by five\nlieees, Misses Tibbie and Susie'\nirant, of Accomac, Mrs. George W.\ntones, of Richmond, Va., Mrs. Oscar j\nParks, of Onancock, and Mrs. J. J.\nD\u2019Donnell, of Washington, D. C., j\nmd two nephews, Mr. E. Thomas\nCoard, of Fort Worth, Texas, and j\nur. John D. Grant, Jr., of Accomac.:\nMr. Oscar F. Rayfield\n1 Mr. Oscar F. Rayfield, a highly\n?Steemed citizen, died at his home\nit fiioxoml\u2019' Va., Saturday, March J\nhuh, of paralysis, aged sixty-two j\nyears. Funeral sendees were held at:\nBipxom M. E. Church, South, Sun-1\nlay., March 30th, conducted by Rev.i\nZ. V. 'Johnston and Rev. L. Spurgeon j\nClark and interment was in the Ray-\nfield family burying ground- at\nBlbxom.\nThe active pallbearers were Messrs\nWillie Littleton, W. L. Bloxom, W.\nS. Messiyk, Sr., Scctt Littleton, L.:\nli. Young and J. G. Walker. The\nhonorary pallbearers were Messrs, i\nHarold Littleton, Harvey Hall, S. L. i\nChurn, Harry Ackley, Millard roul\nson and Mosby Xortham.\nMr. Rayfield is survived by his\nwidow, Mrs. Bertha Marshall Ray\nfieldy ,one; \u2018daughter, Mrs. Howard\nLittleton, two grandchildren, one'sis-1\nter, Mrs. Sallie Nelson, Modest\nTown, and one brother, Mr. Samuel\nJ. Rayfield, of Mappsville.\nMr. S. James Littleton\nMr. S. James Littleton, a well\nknown and highly respected citizen,\ndied at his home at Bloxom, Va.\u201e\nWednesday, Apiil 2nd, of paraly\nsis, aged seventy-two years. Funeral j\nsen-ices were held at his home,\nThursday, conducted by Rev. Rev.\nZ. V. Johnson and interment was in;\nParksley Cemetery.\nThe active pallbearers were his|\nnephews, Messrs. Sam Hears, Fred f\nMears, Thomas Mears, Edward\nMears, Ralph Phillips, Warren Phil\nlips. The honorary pallbearers were\nMessrs. Vaden Phillips, Otho Wes-1\nsells, William Barnes, J. O. Byrd, j\nWilliam Bunuick, H. T. Mason, Mar- j\nvin White, Jack Bloxom, John Parks,1\nT. L. Hinrnan, James H. Rowley, j\nSam Justis, YV. L. Bloxom, H. A. j\nLittleton, Drs. YYr. W. Kerns and J. j\nW. Bowdoin.\nMr. Littleton is survived by his i\nwidow, Mrs. Meilie Littleton, three i\nsons, Messrs. Howard J. Littleton,!\nWilliam YV. Littleton and Thomas i\nScott Littleton, two sisters, Mrs. L.:\nC. Mears, of Modest Town and Mrs. j\nS. T. Phillips, of Parksley, and one\nbrother, Mr. George Thomas Little-!\nton, of Pocomoke. i\n.Mr*, (r. Thomas Byrd\nMrs. Elizabeth A. Byrd, aged 70;\nyears, wife of Mr. Thomas Byrd j\nof this city passed into the Great!\nBeyond, Saturday night, March 22nd,'\naround the hour of J o\u2019clock, fol-1\nlowing an illness of only a few\nhours.\nI\nMrs. Byrd was a woman of fine\nmoral c haracter, a devoted wife and\nmother, who lived a Christian life,\nand died the Christian death. Of a!\ngentle, kind and unassuming manner,]\nher passing was as quiet and peace\nful as he r life had been heauti-j\nUrn Truly it may be said of her,.\n\"She hath not lived in vain,\u201d for!\nsurely a life so lived cannot go\ncut without having left behind an\ninestimable influence for good.\nBesides her husband Mrs. Byrd is\nsurvived by four daughters and one'\nsoil, Mrs. Abel Bell, 0f Wachaprea-;\ngue, a.. Mrs. Howard A. Young,\nof Chester, Pa., Mrs. Arthur Dough-1\nty. of New York, Mrs. J. L.\nCraig. ,,f Chcraw, S. C., and William,\nJ. Byrd, of Baltimore, Md. She is!\nalso survived by a number of grand-!\nchildren a ad one great grandchild.\nFuneral services were held in\nBethany M. P. Church, this citv.i\nTuesday morning at 10:30 o\u2019clock, I\nconducted by the pastor Kev. E. L. I\nBunee. Her remains were laid to\nrest in Bethany M. P. Cemetery. Hie\npallbearers were Howard A. Youngr,\nAbel Bell, J. L. Craig, L. Chester\nYoung, J. R. Ford and James Lam\nbertson.\u2014Worcester Democrat, Poco\nrnolce City, Md.\nIN MKMORIAM\nA tribute of love and devotion to\nour dear wife and mother, Bertie\nBonniwell, who departed this life\nApril 6. 1921).\nYou suffered hours, yes hours of\npain,\nTo wait for cure but all in vain,\nGod alone knew what was best,\nHe called you home to give you rest.\nIt was late one Saturday night,\nWe shall never forget that day,\nWhen an angel came and whispered,\nI must take your loved one away.\nShe passed away like a summer\nbreeze,\nWith scarce a parting sigh,\nShe passed away from this dark\nworld,\nTo dwell with Christ on high.\nBroken is the family circle,\nSince our loved one went away,\nFrom earth and earthly darkness,\nInto bright and perfect day.\nRest on dear wife and mother,\nYour labor is o\u2019er,\nThy willing hands\nWill toil no more.\nA faithful mother both true and\nkind,\nA truer wife you could never find.\nFor all of us she did her best,\nGod grant her eternal rest.\nHusband and Son,\nLee and Garnett Bonniwell.\nMISS SHANER\u2019S\nAPPOINTMENTS\nMiss Roena E. Shaner, national\nW. C. T. U. organizer and lecturer,'\nis a native of Missouri. She is:\nbrainy, brilliant and versatile. Hear1\nher at the folowing places:\nTuesday, April 8th, 7:30 p. m.\u2014\nMelfa M. E. Church.\nWednesday, April 9th, 2.30 p. m.\u2014\u2022\nW. M. U. Meeting, Onancock.\nWednesday, April 9th, 7:30 p. m.\u2014\nWachapreague M. E. Church.\nThursday, April 10th, 7:30 p. m.\u2014\nMakemie Park.\nFriday, April 11th\u2014Group Meet\ning Guilford.\nFriday, April 11. 7:30 p. m.\u2014\nWoodbury M. E. Church.\nSunday. April 13th, at 11 a. m.\u2014\nZion Baptist Church.\nSunday, April 13th, at 7:30 p. m.\u2014\nUnion Service Parksley.\nTuesday, April 15th\u2014Group Meet\ning, Greenbaekville.\nWednesday, April 16th, at 7:30 p.\nm.\u2014Belle Haven M. E. Church,\nSouth.\nMAY CONSTRUCT\nNEW BRIDGE TO\nCHINCOTEAGUE\nContinued from page 1\nby bridge company and their propo\nsition does not include same. I am\nendeavoring' to adjust in accordance\nwith my understanding that clear\ntitle would be forthcoming. If un\nsuccessful shall recommend at April\nmeeting that construction of new\nroad and bridges be immediately\nbegun. May I therefore ask that the\nnow ssary preliminary engineering\nwork be commenced at once.\u201d\nSenator Warner Ames is counsel\nfor th? highway commission in the\nnegotiations, and Brooks Mapp is\npresident of the Chincoteague Bridge\nCompany, whose property the state\nagreed to take over for .$150,000 July\n1.\nAs contrasted with the $150,000\nwhich the commission agreed to pay\nth? bridge company for its property\nin order to reimburse the stockhold\ners for their expenditures when the\nstate did not have the money to\nfinance the project, it. ^estimated,\nMajor Truxtun saidv that the state\ncan parallel the company's facilities\nfor the same amount as agreed upon\nfor the purchase with the company,\nprovided clear title was given to all\nnecessary property. Engineers have\nalso reported that an immediate ex\npenditure of \u00a770,000 would be need\ned to replace and strengthen bridges\nand widen the cSilseway of the pres\nent connection, if the State took over\nthe property, with the improvements\nin all to cost $100,000.\nFor the $250,000 estimated as\nnecessary to expend on the Chinco\nteague project, including the cost of\nthe present bridge, Major Truxtun\nexpressed: the opinion, the new brid\nges and causeways could be built,\nand the Chincoteague road hard-sur\nfaced or a new road built part of\n^hei Wav .to the present state high\nway. However, he stated the com\nmission felt the bridge stockholders\nshould be reimbursed, provided the\ncompany gave a clear title to its\nHE biggest stock of best\ntires for passenger cars\nand trucks anywhere around\nare right here. They\u2019re\nfor service as well as name.\nAlso they\u2019re \u2022\u2018bonded\" for ser\nvice in writing against all\nhazards for a definite length of\ntime. A 29x4.40 is $7.40 or\n$5.65 for th ceheaper grade.\n\u201cGIANTS\u201d\nWilson\u2019s\nand see for\nly Ourself\nproperty and the approaches.\n\u201cThe commission has *been anxious\nto do the riirht thing: hy the bridge\ncompany stockholders, ami certainly\nexpected it to furnish title to the ap\npiroaohes, for we could not permit\nthe state to buy into a law suit or\nthe bridge to come to a dead end\non the Chincoteaerue side,\u201d explained\nMajor Truxtun. \u201cHowever, the time\nhas come, to quit parleying and as\nsure the Chincoteague Island a free\ntoll bridge without delay.\u201d\nBIJOU\nTHEATRE\nONLEY, VIRGINIA\nShows begin \u00bbt 8 p. m.\nexcept Saturdays\nMON. Tl'ES. April 7 8\nGreta Garbo in\n\u201cTHE KISS\u201d\nA romantic story acclaimed\nas another sensational triumph\nfor this most famous of Holly*\nwood\u2019s stars. If you thrill to\nlove and romance, see Greta\nGarbo in \u201cThe Kiss.\u201d\nAdded\u2014Talking Comedy.\nTHl\u2019RS. &.FRI. April 10 11\nThe Amazing Man of Destiny\nGeorge Arliss in\n\u201cDISRAELI\u201d\nwith Joan Bennett, Ernest\n'Torrence and Florence\nArlisr,\nOne of the most fascinating\nfigures of the past century\nbrought to the talking screen\nthrough the magic Vitaphone\nand the art of a master actor.\n\u201cDisraeli\u201d the -wit and ladies\u2019\nfavorite, the keen and far-see\ning diplomat, who survived the\njeers, racial prejudices and\ntraditions to become England\u2019s\nPrime Minister and a Queen\u2019s\nfavorite. A dramatic master\npiece\u2014See, Hear \u201cDisraeli!\u201d\nAdded\u2014Movietone act.\nAdmission 50 and 25 .ents.\nSATURDAY April 12\n\u201cOH YEAH\u201d\nwith Robert Armstrong and\nJames Gleason\nFrom the Saturday Evening\nPost story, \u201cOh Yeah\u201d is a\nclever adaption of the hit, \u201cIs\nZat Sb?\u201d This famous pair\nof comedians enjoy a frolic and\na fight as well as two rough\nneck railroad brakemen. They\nare as likable a team of amus\ning fellows as you could hope\nto see.\nAdded\u2014Talking Comedy.\nFREE!\nStarting Saturday\nApril 5th\n$5.00\nHAT\nWith every Young Man\u2019s Suit from\n#25.00 to #35.00, including 2 Pairs\nTrousers. All New Shades and Styles.\nPrices of 2 Trousers\nSuits\n$25.00 $27.50\n$30.00 $35.00\nYou will find our stock complete\nin every department\nBostonian Shoes\nFor Men and Boys\nMark C. Callahan\nNV\\t Door to Matthews Lankford\nPocomoke City, Md.\nThe New Queen Quality\nModels Are Here\nThis season each lovely frock in the new silhouette de\nmands its very own shoes shoes tv match its sleeping\ngraciousness of lint*, its flattering femininity.\nThis seeming extravagance, Queen Quality shows you how\nto accomplish with the utmost smartness and with\nperfect economy as well.\nWe illustrate; here just one of the many new styles we\nare showing. .w..v\nThis is a very, smart Step-In in a beautiful soft dull\nli\n.u<i\nKU&t 1''-'\nA\nblack kid\n$6.50\npair\nIn stock \u201cAA,\u201d \u201cA\u201d and B.\u201d\nOthers in newest beige and browri tones, Patents &c. 5\n$6.50 $7.00 $8.50\nVIRGINIA\nSpring Has Come\n\nCURLEE Suits and Topcoats for Spring have arrived!\nThat\u2019s an announcement of no casual interest. It never\nfails to create a stir among men who are alert to style\nvalues. Those who know the integrity of manufacture,\nthe fine fabrics and good tailoring, the smart styling and\nclever patterns of Curlee Clothes, will be among the first\nto; welcome our announcement. To them we say come\nin and see this smart Spuing line.\nGEORGE W. THOMAS CO.\nI 339 Granby St.\nj NORFOLK, VIRGINIA\nI Presenting the Smart Shoes for Men and\nWomen for Spring and SummerWear\nWell riikde shoes of the newest leathers, built on the smart\nnew Spring ami Summer lasts, are now on display. Styles range\nfrom conservative town shoes to heavy weight brogues for country\nand sports wear. These shoes are of excellent quality, high gratae\nworkmanship and Mill give you long wear and comfort.\nUSED NEW TYPE FORDS!\n1 New Model Ford Truck and 1 new 